al inbox / one card."},"183":{"id":"/concepts/deep-links-32","page_id":"/concepts/deep-links","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/deep-links#route-grammar","content":"`#schedules`, `#schedules/:id`"},"184":{"id":"/concepts/deep-links-33","page_id":"/concepts/deep-links","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/deep-links#route-grammar","content":"Schedules / one schedule."},"185":{"id":"/concepts/deep-links-34","page_id":"/concepts/deep-links","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/deep-links#route-grammar","content":"`#agents/agents`, `#agents/skills`, `#agents/knowledge`"},"186":{"id":"/concepts/deep-links-35","page_id":"/concepts/deep-links","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/deep-links#route-grammar","content":"The shared catalogs (append `/:slug` for one entry)."},"187":{"id":"/concepts/deep-links-36","page_id":"/concepts/deep-links","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/deep-links#route-grammar","content":"`#runners`"},"188":{"id":"/concepts/deep-links-37","page_id":"/concepts/deep-links","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/deep-links#route-grammar","content":"Runner health and pool."},"189":{"id":"/concepts/deep-links-38","page_id":"/concepts/deep-links","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/deep-links#route-grammar","content":"`#tokens`, `#secrets`, `#audit`, `#settings`, `#connect`"},"190":{"id":"/concepts/deep-links-39","page_id":"/concepts/deep-links","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/deep-links#route-grammar","content":"Admin and setup views."},"191":{"id":"/concepts/deep-links-40","page_id":"/concepts/deep-links","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/deep-links#route-grammar","content":"Segments are URL-encoded, so ids and slugs with special characters remain valid links. Some tabs accept aliases (for example `visual` for `graph`, `source` for `code`)."},"192":{"id":"/concepts/deep-links-41","page_id":"/concepts/deep-links","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/deep-links#deep-links-in-api-payloads","content":"The API hands these links back so agents and integrations can point humans at the right screen without building URLs themselves:"},"193":{"id":"/concepts/deep-links-42","page_id":"/concepts/deep-links","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/deep-links#deep-links-in-api-payloads","content":"Approval cards carry `deepLink` (the card) and `deepLinkRun` (the linked run), and their `context` includes workflow and run deep links."},"194":{"id":"/concepts/deep-links-43","page_id":"/concepts/deep-links","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/deep-links#deep-links-in-api-payloads","content":"Run-creating responses (`run_workflow`, schedule run-now, draft submit) include link objects for following the run — its status, events, and artifacts endpoints."},"195":{"id":"/concepts/deep-links-44","page_id":"/concepts/deep-links","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/deep-links#deep-links-in-api-payloads","content":"When an agent hands off to a human — \"approve this\", \"read the logs\" — prefer relaying the payload's deep link over describing where to click."},"196":{"id":"/concepts/hooks","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","type":"page","content":"Hooks","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Concepts"],"tags":[],"url":"/concepts/hooks"},"197":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-0","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks","content":"Post-run hook profiles - admin-defined, bounded side effects selected per run that never fail a green run."},"198":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-1","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/hooks#profiles-are-bounded-on-purpose","content":"Profiles are bounded on purpose"},"199":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-2","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/hooks#selecting-hooks-per-run","content":"Selecting hooks per run"},"200":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-3","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/hooks#hook-outcomes-never-turn-a-green-run-red","content":"Hook outcomes never turn a green run red"},"201":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-4","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/hooks#api--mcp","content":"API & MCP"},"202":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-5","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks","content":"A **post-run hook profile** is an admin-authored recipe for an optional side effect — publishing static output, pushing a work branch, calling a webhook — that runs *after* a run has produced its verified artifacts and its gates have passed. Hooks separate \"the work succeeded\" from \"the side effect happened\": callers opt in per run, and hook outcomes never rewrite a run's status."},"203":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-6","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#profiles-are-bounded-on-purpose","content":"Each profile has a fixed `kind` with a fixed set of config keys — anything else is rejected, so raw credentials or ad-hoc shell fragments can never be smuggled into a profile:"},"204":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-7","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#profiles-are-bounded-on-purpose","content":"Kind"},"205":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-8","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#profiles-are-bounded-on-purpose","content":"Effect"},"206":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-9","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#profiles-are-bounded-on-purpose","content":"`static-publish`"},"207":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-10","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#profiles-are-bounded-on-purpose","content":"Copy verified artifacts to a configured target root (optionally with a public URL base)."},"208":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-11","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#profiles-are-bounded-on-purpose","content":"`git-push`"},"209":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-12","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#profiles-are-bounded-on-purpose","content":"Push a work branch to a configured remote. Protected branches (`main`, `master`) are refused — merging to the default branch stays behind explicit run promotion."},"210":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-13","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#profiles-are-bounded-on-purpose","content":"`webhook`"},"211":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-14","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#profiles-are-bounded-on-purpose","content":"POST/PUT to an https URL, with optional headers and secret-backed headers."},"212":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-15","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#profiles-are-bounded-on-purpose","content":"`vercel-preview`"},"213":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-16","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#profiles-are-bounded-on-purpose","content":"Trigger a preview deploy for a configured project."},"214":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-17","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#profiles-are-bounded-on-purpose","content":"`custom-script`"},"215":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-18","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#profiles-are-bounded-on-purpose","content":"Run an allowlisted absolute command with declared, typed arguments — never a shell."},"216":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-19","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#profiles-are-bounded-on-purpose","content":"Profiles reference secrets by **name only** (`secretNames`), declare typed `params` callers may fill, and can restrict which workflows may use them (`allowedCapabilities`)."},"217":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-20","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#selecting-hooks-per-run","content":"Selection is explicit and two-sided:"},"218":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-21","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#selecting-hooks-per-run","content":"The workflow must opt in via `workflow.hooks.allowedProfiles` (a list of profile slugs, or `\"*\"`); no opt-in means no hooks, default-closed."},"219":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-22","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#selecting-hooks-per-run","content":"The caller selects profiles per run with `input.postRunHooks: [\"publish-docs\", …]`."},"220":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-23","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#selecting-hooks-per-run","content":"Preflight rejects a request naming a profile that is disabled or not allowed for that workflow, so ineligible hooks surface before a run is created."},"221":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-24","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#selecting-hooks-per-run","content":"Non-admin callers see enabled profiles in a caller-safe shape (slug, name, kind, params) — no paths, remotes, URLs, or secret names. Admins with `?all=1` see every profile with full config and readiness."},"222":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-25","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#hook-outcomes-never-turn-a-green-run-red","content":"Hooks run after the run's gates pass, and their results are reported separately from the run status:"},"223":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-26","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#hook-outcomes-never-turn-a-green-run-red","content":"Outcome"},"224":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-27","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#hook-outcomes-never-turn-a-green-run-red","content":"Meaning"},"225":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-28","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#hook-outcomes-never-turn-a-green-run-red","content":"`succeeded`"},"226":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-29","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#hook-outcomes-never-turn-a-green-run-red","content":"The side effect completed."},"227":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-30","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#hook-outcomes-never-turn-a-green-run-red","content":"`hook_failed`"},"228":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-31","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#hook-outcomes-never-turn-a-green-run-red","content":"The side effect itself failed."},"229":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-32","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#hook-outcomes-never-turn-a-green-run-red","content":"`hook_config_required`"},"230":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-33","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#hook-outcomes-never-turn-a-green-run-red","content":"The profile cannot execute — typically missing named secrets or a disabled secret store."},"231":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-34","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#hook-outcomes-never-turn-a-green-run-red","content":"`hook_blocked`"},"232":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-35","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#hook-outcomes-never-turn-a-green-run-red","content":"The profile was not eligible for this run."},"233":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-36","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#hook-outcomes-never-turn-a-green-run-red","content":"`skipped`"},"234":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-37","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#hook-outcomes-never-turn-a-green-run-red","content":"The hook did not run."},"235":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-38","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#hook-outcomes-never-turn-a-green-run-red","content":"A failed hook never rewrites a successful run into a failed one: the run keeps its own status and the hook results ride in the run output, aggregated into one headline hook status. `POST /api/hooks/{slug}/validate` is the admin dry-run: it reports `hook_config_required` with missing secret *names* only."},"236":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-39","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#api--mcp","content":"Endpoint"},"237":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-40","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#api--mcp","content":"MCP tool"},"238":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-41","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#api--mcp","content":"Notes"},"239":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-42","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#api--mcp","content":"`GET /api/hooks`"},"240":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-43","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#api--mcp","content":"`list_hooks`"},"241":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-44","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#api--mcp","content":"`?workflow=<slug>` narrows; admin `?all=1` includes disabled."},"242":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-45","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#api--mcp","content":"`GET /api/hooks/{slug}`"},"243":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-46","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#api--mcp","content":"`get_hook`"},"244":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-47","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#api--mcp","content":"`POST /api/hooks`, `PATCH /api/hooks/{slug}`"},"245":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-48","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#api--mcp","content":"`upsert_hook`"},"246":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-49","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#api--mcp","content":"Admin."},"247":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-50","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#api--mcp","content":"`POST /api/hooks/{slug}/validate`"},"248":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-51","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#api--mcp","content":"`validate_hook`"},"249":{"id":"/concepts/hooks-52","page_id":"/concepts/hooks","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/hooks#api--mcp","content":"Admin readiness dry-run."},"250":{"id":"/concepts","page_id":"/concepts","type":"page","content":"Concepts","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Concepts"],"tags":[],"url":"/concepts"},"251":{"id":"/concepts-0","page_id":"/concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts","content":"A map of the core Runyard concepts and how they fit together."},"252":{"id":"/concepts-1","page_id":"/concepts","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts#the-catalog","content":"The catalog"},"253":{"id":"/concepts-2","page_id":"/concepts","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts#execution","content":"Execution"},"254":{"id":"/concepts-3","page_id":"/concepts","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts#control","content":"Control"},"255":{"id":"/concepts-4","page_id":"/concepts","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts#platform","content":"Platform"},"256":{"id":"/concepts-5","page_id":"/concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts","content":"Runyard is a self-hosted control plane for agent runs. You install **workflows** into a catalog, start **runs** of those workflows from the API, MCP, web app, or a **schedule**, and **runners** claim and execute them. Anything that needs a human decision surfaces as an **approval** card, sensitive values live in the encrypted **secrets** store, and optional side effects after a run are handled by admin-defined **hooks**. Access is governed by scoped **tokens**, and every page in the Hub is a shareable **deep link**."},"257":{"id":"/concepts-6","page_id":"/concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts#the-catalog","content":"**Workflows** — the unit of the catalog: a named, versioned definition with input/output schemas whose source lives as immutable bundles in the Hub database."},"258":{"id":"/concepts-7","page_id":"/concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts#the-catalog","content":"**Agents, skills & knowledge** — shared, reusable building blocks (agent roles, skills, knowledge resources) that workflows reference."},"259":{"id":"/concepts-8","page_id":"/concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts#execution","content":"**Runs** — a single execution of a workflow: lifecycle statuses, preflight and run drafts, events, logs, artifacts, reruns, and promotion."},"260":{"id":"/concepts-9","page_id":"/concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts#execution","content":"**Runners** — the machines that claim queued runs and execute them via the Smithers engine, with tags, capacity, and optional sandboxing."},"261":{"id":"/concepts-10","page_id":"/concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts#execution","content":"**Schedules** — cron or one-shot triggers that create ordinary runs on a cadence."},"262":{"id":"/concepts-11","page_id":"/concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts#control","content":"**Approvals** — declared human decisions: approval cards with an explicit ask, per-kind consequences, and optional timers with fallbacks."},"263":{"id":"/concepts-12","page_id":"/concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts#control","content":"**Hooks** — admin-defined post-run side effects (publish, push, webhook) that run after a run's gates pass and never fail a green run."},"264":{"id":"/concepts-13","page_id":"/concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts#platform","content":"**Tokens & scopes** — bearer-token auth with the `api`, `mcp`, `runner`, `approvals`, and `admin` scopes; browser sessions carry exactly a token's scopes."},"265":{"id":"/concepts-14","page_id":"/concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts#platform","content":"**Secrets** — an encrypted store whose values are only ever decrypted into a run's child process environment, never returned by the API."},"266":{"id":"/concepts-15","page_id":"/concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts#platform","content":"**Deep links** — the shareable URL grammar of the Hub web app, plus the deep links the API returns in its payloads."},"267":{"id":"/concepts/runners","page_id":"/concepts/runners","type":"page","content":"Runners","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Concepts"],"tags":[],"url":"/concepts/runners"},"268":{"id":"/concepts/runners-0","page_id":"/concepts/runners","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runners","content":"The machines that claim and execute runs via the Smithers engine - registration, tags, capacity, health, and sandboxing."},"269":{"id":"/concepts/runners-1","page_id":"/concepts/runners","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/runners#registration-heartbeat-claim","content":"Registration, heartbeat, claim"},"270":{"id":"/concepts/runners-2","page_id":"/concepts/runners","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/runners#tags-and-execution-modes","content":"Tags and execution modes"},"271":{"id":"/concepts/runners-3","page_id":"/concepts/runners","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/runners#capacity-and-pool","content":"Capacity and pool"},"272":{"id":"/concepts/runners-4","page_id":"/concepts/runners","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/runners#sandboxing","content":"Sandboxing"},"273":{"id":"/concepts/runners-5","page_id":"/concepts/runners","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/runners#api--mcp","content":"API & MCP"},"274":{"id":"/concepts/runners-6","page_id":"/concepts/runners","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runners","content":"A **runner** is a machine that executes runs. Runners run the Runyard runner process, which claims queued runs from the Hub and executes each workflow via the **Smithers engine** (`smithers up <workflow> --input <json>`), spawning the local agent CLI as the worker. Nothing is faked: the agent runs on the runner's machine, and the Hub is the durable record — events stream back as run events, and outputs and traces are uploaded as artifacts."},"275":{"id":"/concepts/runners-7","page_id":"/concepts/runners","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runners#registration-heartbeat-claim","content":"Runners speak a small machine protocol authenticated with **runner-scoped tokens** (see Tokens & scopes):"},"276":{"id":"/concepts/runners-8","page_id":"/concepts/runners","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runners#registration-heartbeat-claim","content":"`POST /api/runners/register` — announce name, hostname, platform, version, tags, and capacity."},"277":{"id":"/concepts/runners-9","page_id":"/concepts/runners","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runners#registration-heartbeat-claim","content":"`POST /api/runners/{id}/heartbeat` — periodic liveness; a stale heartbeat marks the runner offline."},"278":{"id":"/concepts/runners-10","page_id":"/concepts/runners","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runners#registration-heartbeat-claim","content":"`GET /api/runners/{id}/next-run` — claim the next matching queued run. The claim payload carries everything the run needs, including decrypted secrets for that run only."},"279":{"id":"/concepts/runners-11","page_id":"/concepts/runners","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runners#registration-heartbeat-claim","content":"Run lifecycle reports (`start`, events, `complete`, `fail`, artifact upload) are restricted to the runner that owns the run: the Hub checks the claiming token's identity, so one runner's token cannot touch another runner's runs."},"280":{"id":"/concepts/runners-12","page_id":"/concepts/runners","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runners#tags-and-execution-modes","content":"Runners advertise **tags** (for example `local` on a workstation, `vps` on a shared remote pool). Two things match runs to runners:"},"281":{"id":"/concepts/runners-13","page_id":"/concepts/runners","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runners#tags-and-execution-modes","content":"A workflow's `requiredRunnerTags` must all be present on the runner."},"282":{"id":"/concepts/runners-14","page_id":"/concepts/runners","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runners#tags-and-execution-modes","content":"The caller's execution intent: `executionMode: \"local\" | \"remote\" | \"auto\"` (optionally a specific `runnerLocation`). `remote` targets the shared remote/VPS pool (default location `vps`); `auto` takes any matching runner."},"283":{"id":"/concepts/runners-15","page_id":"/concepts/runners","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runners#tags-and-execution-modes","content":"Preflight checks this matching up front and reports `no_matching_runner` (blocker) or `runners_offline` (warning — the run would queue until one returns)."},"284":{"id":"/concepts/runners-16","page_id":"/concepts/runners","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runners#capacity-and-pool","content":"Each runner declares a `capacity` (concurrent run slots) and reports its active runs; the Hub assigns work only to free slots. `GET /api/runners` returns every registered runner with heartbeat state, capacity, active slots, plus a pool summary — the same data the **Runners** page in the web app shows (`#runners`)."},"285":{"id":"/concepts/runners-17","page_id":"/concepts/runners","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runners#sandboxing","content":"By default the runner executes workflows directly on its host. Setting `RUNNER_SANDBOX=bubblewrap` on the runner wraps each workflow *launch* in a generated Bubblewrap (`bwrap`) sandbox: the run's workspace is the only writable mount (bound at the same path inside and out), system directories are bound read-only, and the child gets a fresh workspace-local `HOME` — the host home directory, with its keys and credentials, is never mounted. Polling and control commands stay outside the sandbox. Installing `bwrap` is the deployer's responsibility; the runner verifies at startup that the sandbox actually works before claiming runs."},"286":{"id":"/concepts/runners-18","page_id":"/concepts/runners","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runners#api--mcp","content":"Endpoint"},"287":{"id":"/concepts/runners-19","page_id":"/concepts/runners","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runners#api--mcp","content":"MCP tool"},"288":{"id":"/concepts/runners-20","page_id":"/concepts/runners","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runners#api--mcp","content":"Notes"},"289":{"id":"/concepts/runners-21","page_id":"/concepts/runners","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runners#api--mcp","content":"`GET /api/runners`"},"290":{"id":"/concepts/runners-22","page_id":"/concepts/runners","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runners#api--mcp","content":"`list_runners`"},"291":{"id":"/concepts/runners-23","page_id":"/concepts/runners","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runners#api--mcp","content":"Runners, heartbeat state, capacity, slots, pool summary."},"292":{"id":"/concepts/runners-24","page_id":"/concepts/runners","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runners#api--mcp","content":"`POST /api/runners/register`"},"293":{"id":"/concepts/runners-25","page_id":"/concepts/runners","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runners#api--mcp","content":"—"},"294":{"id":"/concepts/runners-26","page_id":"/concepts/runners","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runners#api--mcp","content":"Runner protocol (runner scope)."},"295":{"id":"/concepts/runners-27","page_id":"/concepts/runners","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runners#api--mcp","content":"`POST /api/runners/{id}/heartbeat`"},"296":{"id":"/concepts/runners-28","page_id":"/concepts/runners","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runners#api--mcp","content":"—"},"297":{"id":"/concepts/runners-29","page_id":"/concepts/runners","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runners#api--mcp","content":"Runner protocol."},"298":{"id":"/concepts/runners-30","page_id":"/concepts/runners","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runners#api--mcp","content":"`GET /api/runners/{id}/next-run`"},"299":{"id":"/concepts/runners-31","page_id":"/concepts/runners","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runners#api--mcp","content":"—"},"300":{"id":"/concepts/runners-32","page_id":"/concepts/runners","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runners#api--mcp","content":"Runner protocol; claims the next run."},"301":{"id":"/concepts/runners-33","page_id":"/concepts/runners","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runners#api--mcp","content":"`POST /api/runs/{id}/start` / `/complete` / `/fail` / `/events` / `/artifacts`"},"302":{"id":"/concepts/runners-34","page_id":"/concepts/runners","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runners#api--mcp","content":"—"},"303":{"id":"/concepts/runners-35","page_id":"/concepts/runners","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runners#api--mcp","content":"Runner protocol; run ownership enforced."},"304":{"id":"/concepts/runners-36","page_id":"/concepts/runners","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runners#api--mcp","content":"The runner protocol endpoints intentionally have no MCP tools — they are Hub↔runner machinery, not an operator surface."},"305":{"id":"/concepts/runs","page_id":"/concepts/runs","type":"page","content":"Runs","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Concepts"],"tags":[],"url":"/concepts/runs"},"306":{"id":"/concepts/runs-0","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs","content":"The run lifecycle, preflight and run drafts, events and artifacts, reruns, and promotion."},"307":{"id":"/concepts/runs-1","page_id":"/concepts/runs","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/runs#lifecycle","content":"Lifecycle"},"308":{"id":"/concepts/runs-2","page_id":"/concepts/runs","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/runs#failure-classes","content":"Failure classes"},"309":{"id":"/concepts/runs-3","page_id":"/concepts/runs","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/runs#preflight-and-run-drafts-negotiation","content":"Preflight and run drafts (negotiation)"},"310":{"id":"/concepts/runs-4","page_id":"/concepts/runs","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/runs#events-timeline-logs-artifacts","content":"Events, timeline, logs, artifacts"},"311":{"id":"/concepts/runs-5","page_id":"/concepts/runs","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/runs#reruns-and-promotion","content":"Reruns and promotion"},"312":{"id":"/concepts/runs-6","page_id":"/concepts/runs","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/runs#response-endpoints","content":"Response endpoints"},"313":{"id":"/concepts/runs-7","page_id":"/concepts/runs","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/runs#api--mcp","content":"API & MCP"},"314":{"id":"/concepts/runs-8","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs","content":"A **run** is a single execution of a workflow with a JSON input. Runs are created from the API, MCP, web app, CLI, a schedule, or a workflow endpoint; a runner claims each queued run and executes it, streaming events, logs, and artifacts back to the Hub as the durable record."},"315":{"id":"/concepts/runs-9","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#lifecycle","content":"Status"},"316":{"id":"/concepts/runs-10","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#lifecycle","content":"Meaning"},"317":{"id":"/concepts/runs-11","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#lifecycle","content":"`waiting_approval`"},"318":{"id":"/concepts/runs-12","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#lifecycle","content":"Held for a human decision before entering the queue (see Approvals). Never times out — waiting cannot fail a run."},"319":{"id":"/concepts/runs-13","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#lifecycle","content":"`queued`"},"320":{"id":"/concepts/runs-14","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#lifecycle","content":"Ready for a matching runner to claim."},"321":{"id":"/concepts/runs-15","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#lifecycle","content":"`assigned`"},"322":{"id":"/concepts/runs-16","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#lifecycle","content":"Claimed by a runner, not yet started."},"323":{"id":"/concepts/runs-17","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#lifecycle","content":"`running`"},"324":{"id":"/concepts/runs-18","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#lifecycle","content":"Executing on the runner."},"325":{"id":"/concepts/runs-19","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#lifecycle","content":"`succeeded`"},"326":{"id":"/concepts/runs-20","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#lifecycle","content":"Finished with outputs."},"327":{"id":"/concepts/runs-21","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#lifecycle","content":"`cancelled`"},"328":{"id":"/concepts/runs-22","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#lifecycle","content":"Stopped by an operator or a rejected approval — a human \"no\" is a decision, not a failure."},"329":{"id":"/concepts/runs-23","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#lifecycle","content":"`failed` (+ classes)"},"330":{"id":"/concepts/runs-24","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#lifecycle","content":"Terminal failure; see failure classes below."},"331":{"id":"/concepts/runs-25","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#lifecycle","content":"Terminal states are final: late reports racing a terminal state are absorbed idempotently rather than overwriting the first decision."},"332":{"id":"/concepts/runs-26","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#failure-classes","content":"Failures are classified into specific terminal statuses so operators can tell config problems from real failures: `failed` (generic), `blocked_by_gate` (a verification gate failed), `blocked_by_preflight` (the run could never start as configured), `provider_limited` (rate limits/quota), `timed_out`, `invalid_output` (schema mismatch), `infra_unavailable` (network/runner infrastructure), and `needs_human`."},"333":{"id":"/concepts/runs-27","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#preflight-and-run-drafts-negotiation","content":"Before anything is enqueued, Runyard can run a **deterministic preflight**: schema checks on required input fields, runner/tag availability, secret presence, hook eligibility, and workflow source resolution. The result is `ready`, `needs_input` (with `questions[]` the caller can answer), or `blocked` (with `blockers[]` only an operator can fix), plus warnings, suggested defaults, and a `nextAction` hint."},"334":{"id":"/concepts/runs-28","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#preflight-and-run-drafts-negotiation","content":"Three ways to use it:"},"335":{"id":"/concepts/runs-29","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#preflight-and-run-drafts-negotiation","content":"`POST /api/workflows/{id}/preflight` — stateless report, nothing created."},"336":{"id":"/concepts/runs-30","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#preflight-and-run-drafts-negotiation","content":"`POST /api/workflows/{id}/run` with `negotiate: true` — enqueue only when ready; otherwise the negotiation state and a saved draft come back instead of a doomed run."},"337":{"id":"/concepts/runs-31","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#preflight-and-run-drafts-negotiation","content":"**Run drafts** — a draft is a proposed run that has *not* been enqueued. Create it, patch its input to answer questions (each patch re-preflights), then submit; submit re-preflights and returns 202 with the run only when ready (422 `needs_input` / 409 `blocked` otherwise)."},"338":{"id":"/concepts/runs-32","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#preflight-and-run-drafts-negotiation","content":"`input.title` is recommended for agent-created runs: a short human-readable title used in run lists, approval cards, and handoff."},"339":{"id":"/concepts/runs-33","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#events-timeline-logs-artifacts","content":"Runners append structured **events** as the run progresses; `GET /api/runs/{id}/events/stream` serves them live over SSE and `GET /api/runs/{id}/timeline` merges status transitions, events, and artifacts into one ascending feed (with `since`/`limit` paging). Log lines are at `/logs`, a condensed log summary and diagnostics at `/diagnostics`, and uploaded **artifacts** (outputs, traces, files) at `/artifacts`, downloadable by artifact id."},"340":{"id":"/concepts/runs-34","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#reruns-and-promotion","content":"**Rerun** — `POST /api/runs/{id}/rerun` creates a linked new run with the same input, optionally edited."},"341":{"id":"/concepts/runs-35","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#reruns-and-promotion","content":"**Promotion** — for runs that mutated an isolated git worktree, `POST /api/runs/{id}/promote` merges the successful run's work into its target branch, runs gates, pushes, and cleans up the branch/worktree. Merging to the default branch always goes through promotion, never through a hook."},"342":{"id":"/concepts/runs-36","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#response-endpoints","content":"A run request may include `responseEndpoint: {type: \"http\" | \"telegram\", config}` so the terminal-state reply is delivered to the caller when the run finishes. Delivery state is reported in `responseEndpoints[]` on `GET /api/runs/{id}`; polling that endpoint remains the canonical fallback."},"343":{"id":"/concepts/runs-37","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#api--mcp","content":"Endpoint"},"344":{"id":"/concepts/runs-38","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#api--mcp","content":"MCP tool"},"345":{"id":"/concepts/runs-39","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#api--mcp","content":"`POST /api/workflows/{id}/run`"},"346":{"id":"/concepts/runs-40","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#api--mcp","content":"`run_workflow`"},"347":{"id":"/concepts/runs-41","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#api--mcp","content":"`POST /api/workflows/{id}/preflight`"},"348":{"id":"/concepts/runs-42","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#api--mcp","content":"`preflight_workflow`"},"349":{"id":"/concepts/runs-43","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#api--mcp","content":"`GET/POST /api/run-drafts`, `GET/PATCH /api/run-drafts/{id}`, `POST .../submit`, `POST .../discard`"},"350":{"id":"/concepts/runs-44","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#api--mcp","content":"`list_run_drafts`, `create_run_draft`, `get_run_draft`, `update_run_draft`, `submit_run_draft`, `discard_run_draft`"},"351":{"id":"/concepts/runs-45","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#api--mcp","content":"`GET /api/runs`, `GET /api/runs/{id}`"},"352":{"id":"/concepts/runs-46","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#api--mcp","content":"`list_runs`, `get_run_status`"},"353":{"id":"/concepts/runs-47","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#api--mcp","content":"`GET /api/runs/{id}/events`, `/timeline`, `/diagnostics`, `/logs`"},"354":{"id":"/concepts/runs-48","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#api--mcp","content":"`get_run_events`, `get_run_timeline`, `get_run_diagnostics`, `get_run_logs`"},"355":{"id":"/concepts/runs-49","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#api--mcp","content":"`GET /api/runs/{id}/artifacts`, `GET /api/artifacts`, `GET /api/artifacts/{id}/download`"},"356":{"id":"/concepts/runs-50","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#api--mcp","content":"`get_run_artifacts`, `search_artifacts`, `download_artifact`"},"357":{"id":"/concepts/runs-51","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#api--mcp","content":"`POST /api/runs/{id}/cancel`"},"358":{"id":"/concepts/runs-52","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#api--mcp","content":"`cancel_run`"},"359":{"id":"/concepts/runs-53","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#api--mcp","content":"`POST /api/runs/{id}/rerun`"},"360":{"id":"/concepts/runs-54","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#api--mcp","content":"`rerun_workflow_run`"},"361":{"id":"/concepts/runs-55","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#api--mcp","content":"`POST /api/runs/{id}/promote`"},"362":{"id":"/concepts/runs-56","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#api--mcp","content":"`promote_run`"},"363":{"id":"/concepts/runs-57","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#api--mcp","content":"`GET /api/dashboard`"},"364":{"id":"/concepts/runs-58","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#api--mcp","content":"`get_dashboard`"},"365":{"id":"/concepts/runs-59","page_id":"/concepts/runs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/runs#api--mcp","content":"The `start`/`complete`/`fail`/event-append and artifact-upload endpoints under `/api/runs/{id}` are the runner protocol (runner-scoped tokens, run ownership enforced) — see Runners."},"366":{"id":"/concepts/schedules","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","type":"page","content":"Schedules","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Concepts"],"tags":[],"url":"/concepts/schedules"},"367":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-0","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules","content":"Cron and one-shot triggers that create ordinary workflow runs on a cadence."},"368":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-1","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/schedules#cron-expressions-and-timezones","content":"Cron expressions and timezones"},"369":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-2","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/schedules#one-shot-schedules","content":"One-shot schedules"},"370":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-3","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/schedules#enable-disable-run-now","content":"Enable, disable, run now"},"371":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-4","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/schedules#what-a-fire-produces","content":"What a fire produces"},"372":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-5","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/schedules#api--mcp","content":"API & MCP"},"373":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-6","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules","content":"A **schedule** runs a workflow automatically: either recurring on a **cron** cadence or once at a fixed **runAt** timestamp. Each fire creates a completely ordinary run with the schedule's stored input — it appears in run lists, honors the workflow's approval policy, and is executed by whatever runner matches."},"374":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-7","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#cron-expressions-and-timezones","content":"Runyard uses standard **5-field cron** (`minute hour day-of-month month day-of-week`) with ranges (`a-b`), lists (`a,b,c`), steps (`*/n`, `a-b/n`), month/weekday names (`jan..dec`, `sun..sat`), and the aliases `@yearly`, `@monthly`, `@weekly`, `@daily`, `@hourly`. There is no seconds field — the Hub ticks at minute granularity."},"375":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-8","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#cron-expressions-and-timezones","content":"Every schedule has an **IANA timezone** (default `UTC`); the expression is evaluated against wall-clock time in that zone, so DST shifts are honored."},"376":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-9","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#cron-expressions-and-timezones","content":"The preview returns a human-readable description plus the next fire instants — nothing is created."},"377":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-10","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#one-shot-schedules","content":"Provide `runAt` (an ISO timestamp) instead of `cron` to fire exactly once. A schedule takes one or the other."},"378":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-11","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#enable-disable-run-now","content":"**Disable** stops a schedule from firing without deleting it; **enable** resumes the cadence. Both are admin actions."},"379":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-12","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#enable-disable-run-now","content":"**Run now** fires the schedule immediately without changing its cadence — useful for testing input before the next scheduled fire."},"380":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-13","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#enable-disable-run-now","content":"Each schedule tracks `nextRunAt`, `lastRunAt`, the last run id, and the last fire status, all visible on the Schedules page (`#schedules`) and in the API."},"381":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-14","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#what-a-fire-produces","content":"Every fire dispatches a normal run whose origin identifies the schedule:"},"382":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-15","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#what-a-fire-produces","content":"(`trigger` is `ticker` for cadence fires, `manual` for run-now.) The run also gets a `run.scheduled` event recording the schedule, cron, and timezone. If the workflow's approval policy requires it, the run starts in `waiting_approval` like any other run."},"383":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-16","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#api--mcp","content":"Endpoint"},"384":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-17","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#api--mcp","content":"MCP tool"},"385":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-18","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#api--mcp","content":"Notes"},"386":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-19","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#api--mcp","content":"`GET /api/schedules`"},"387":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-20","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#api--mcp","content":"`list_schedules`"},"388":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-21","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#api--mcp","content":"Includes next/last run and a readable preview."},"389":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-22","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#api--mcp","content":"`GET /api/schedules/preview`"},"390":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-23","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#api--mcp","content":"`preview_schedule`"},"391":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-24","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#api--mcp","content":"Query: `cron`, `timezone`."},"392":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-25","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#api--mcp","content":"`GET /api/schedules/{id}`"},"393":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-26","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#api--mcp","content":"`get_schedule`"},"394":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-27","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#api--mcp","content":"`POST /api/schedules`"},"395":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-28","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#api--mcp","content":"`create_schedule`"},"396":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-29","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#api--mcp","content":"Admin. Body: `name`, `workflowSlug`, `cron` or `runAt`, `timezone`, `input`, `enabled`."},"397":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-30","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#api--mcp","content":"`PATCH /api/schedules/{id}`"},"398":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-31","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#api--mcp","content":"`update_schedule`"},"399":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-32","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#api--mcp","content":"Admin."},"400":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-33","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#api--mcp","content":"`POST /api/schedules/{id}/enable`"},"401":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-34","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#api--mcp","content":"`enable_schedule`"},"402":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-35","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#api--mcp","content":"Admin."},"403":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-36","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#api--mcp","content":"`POST /api/schedules/{id}/disable`"},"404":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-37","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#api--mcp","content":"`disable_schedule`"},"405":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-38","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#api--mcp","content":"Admin."},"406":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-39","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#api--mcp","content":"`POST /api/schedules/{id}/run-now`"},"407":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-40","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#api--mcp","content":"`run_schedule_now`"},"408":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-41","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#api--mcp","content":"Fires immediately; rate-limited."},"409":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-42","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#api--mcp","content":"`DELETE /api/schedules/{id}`"},"410":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-43","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#api--mcp","content":"`delete_schedule`"},"411":{"id":"/concepts/schedules-44","page_id":"/concepts/schedules","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/schedules#api--mcp","content":"Admin."},"412":{"id":"/concepts/secrets","page_id":"/concepts/secrets","type":"page","content":"Secrets","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Concepts"],"tags":[],"url":"/concepts/secrets"},"413":{"id":"/concepts/secrets-0","page_id":"/concepts/secrets","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/secrets","content":"The encrypted secret store - admin-managed, listable by name only, delivered to runs at claim time and never returned by the API."},"414":{"id":"/concepts/secrets-1","page_id":"/concepts/secrets","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/secrets#management-admin-only","content":"Management (admin only)"},"415":{"id":"/concepts/secrets-2","page_id":"/concepts/secrets","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/secrets#how-runs-get-secrets","content":"How runs get secrets"},"416":{"id":"/concepts/secrets-3","page_id":"/concepts/secrets","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/secrets#api--mcp","content":"API & MCP"},"417":{"id":"/concepts/secrets-4","page_id":"/concepts/secrets","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/secrets","content":"Runyard keeps reusable credentials (API keys, deploy tokens) in an **encrypted secret store** on the Hub. Values are encrypted at rest, and the API is deliberately one-way: you can list secret *names and metadata*, set a value, and delete one — **values are never returned** by any list or read endpoint, to any scope."},"418":{"id":"/concepts/secrets-5","page_id":"/concepts/secrets","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/secrets#management-admin-only","content":"Secret names are env-var-safe identifiers, because that is exactly how they are delivered. The whole feature is gated on the store being enabled (an encryption key configured on the Hub); when it is not, secret-dependent runs and hooks report that configuration is required instead of failing obscurely."},"419":{"id":"/concepts/secrets-6","page_id":"/concepts/secrets","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/secrets#how-runs-get-secrets","content":"A run receives the union of:"},"420":{"id":"/concepts/secrets-7","page_id":"/concepts/secrets","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/secrets#how-runs-get-secrets","content":"the workflow's declared `workflow.secrets` list, and"},"421":{"id":"/concepts/secrets-8","page_id":"/concepts/secrets","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/secrets#how-runs-get-secrets","content":"the run input's `input.secretNames` list."},"422":{"id":"/concepts/secrets-9","page_id":"/concepts/secrets","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/secrets#how-runs-get-secrets","content":"Preflight verifies every named secret exists before the run is enqueued. At **claim time** — when a runner claims the run — the Hub decrypts exactly those named secrets into an env map that rides the claim payload, and the runner injects them **only into the workflow's child process environment**. That is the sole path a plaintext value ever leaves the store:"},"423":{"id":"/concepts/secrets-10","page_id":"/concepts/secrets","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/secrets#how-runs-get-secrets","content":"Secrets never appear in run events, logs, or the run record."},"424":{"id":"/concepts/secrets-11","page_id":"/concepts/secrets","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/secrets#how-runs-get-secrets","content":"Stored secret values are additionally scrubbed from run output and artifacts before they are persisted."},"425":{"id":"/concepts/secrets-12","page_id":"/concepts/secrets","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/secrets#how-runs-get-secrets","content":"Payload fields with credential-like names are redacted in approval cards and other presentation surfaces."},"426":{"id":"/concepts/secrets-13","page_id":"/concepts/secrets","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/secrets#how-runs-get-secrets","content":"Other consumers reference secrets **by name only**: hook profiles declare `secretNames`, and their readiness checks report missing *names*, never values."},"427":{"id":"/concepts/secrets-14","page_id":"/concepts/secrets","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/secrets#api--mcp","content":"Endpoint"},"428":{"id":"/concepts/secrets-15","page_id":"/concepts/secrets","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/secrets#api--mcp","content":"MCP tool"},"429":{"id":"/concepts/secrets-16","page_id":"/concepts/secrets","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/secrets#api--mcp","content":"Notes"},"430":{"id":"/concepts/secrets-17","page_id":"/concepts/secrets","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/secrets#api--mcp","content":"`GET /api/secrets`"},"431":{"id":"/concepts/secrets-18","page_id":"/concepts/secrets","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/secrets#api--mcp","content":"`list_secrets`"},"432":{"id":"/concepts/secrets-19","page_id":"/concepts/secrets","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/secrets#api--mcp","content":"Admin. Names and metadata only."},"433":{"id":"/concepts/secrets-20","page_id":"/concepts/secrets","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/secrets#api--mcp","content":"`PUT /api/secrets/{key}`"},"434":{"id":"/concepts/secrets-21","page_id":"/concepts/secrets","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/secrets#api--mcp","content":"`set_secret`"},"435":{"id":"/concepts/secrets-22","page_id":"/concepts/secrets","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/secrets#api--mcp","content":"Admin. `{value, description?}`."},"436":{"id":"/concepts/secrets-23","page_id":"/concepts/secrets","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/secrets#api--mcp","content":"`DELETE /api/secrets/{key}`"},"437":{"id":"/concepts/secrets-24","page_id":"/concepts/secrets","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/secrets#api--mcp","content":"`delete_secret`"},"438":{"id":"/concepts/secrets-25","page_id":"/concepts/secrets","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/secrets#api--mcp","content":"Admin."},"439":{"id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes","page_id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes","type":"page","content":"Tokens & Scopes","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Concepts"],"tags":[],"url":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes"},"440":{"id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes-0","page_id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes","content":"Bearer-token authentication, the five scopes, the bootstrap token, and how browser and Telegram sessions work."},"441":{"id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes-1","page_id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes#scopes","content":"Scopes"},"442":{"id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes-2","page_id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes#bootstrap-token","content":"Bootstrap token"},"443":{"id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes-3","page_id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes#browser-sessions","content":"Browser sessions"},"444":{"id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes-4","page_id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes#telegram-webapp-sessions","content":"Telegram WebApp sessions"},"445":{"id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes-5","page_id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes#api--mcp","content":"API & MCP"},"446":{"id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes-6","page_id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes","content":"Every Runyard API call is authenticated with a **bearer access token**:"},"447":{"id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes-7","page_id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes","content":"`GET /api/me` (or the `whoami` MCP tool) describes the token you are holding: its name and granted scopes. Tokens are issued and revoked by admins and may carry an expiry."},"448":{"id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes-8","page_id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes#scopes","content":"A token carries one or more scopes; each endpoint declares which scopes may call it."},"449":{"id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes-9","page_id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes#scopes","content":"Scope"},"450":{"id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes-10","page_id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes#scopes","content":"Grants"},"451":{"id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes-11","page_id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes#scopes","content":"`api`"},"452":{"id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes-12","page_id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes#scopes","content":"Operating runs: start/preflight workflows, run drafts, reruns, promotion, cancel, resolve approvals."},"453":{"id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes-13","page_id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes#scopes","content":"`mcp`"},"454":{"id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes-14","page_id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes#scopes","content":"The same operating surface for MCP clients."},"455":{"id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes-15","page_id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes#scopes","content":"`runner`"},"456":{"id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes-16","page_id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes#scopes","content":"The runner protocol: register, heartbeat, claim runs, report lifecycle, upload artifacts."},"457":{"id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes-17","page_id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes#scopes","content":"`approvals`"},"458":{"id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes-18","page_id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes#scopes","content":"Resolving and creating approval cards only — the narrow scope for approval surfaces."},"459":{"id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes-19","page_id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes#scopes","content":"`admin`"},"460":{"id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes-20","page_id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes#scopes","content":"Everything. `admin` is a **superscope**: it satisfies every scope requirement, and admin-only endpoints (tokens, secrets, catalog edits, schedules, hooks, audit) require it."},"461":{"id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes-21","page_id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes#scopes","content":"Reads such as listing runs, workflows, runners, or schedules need only an authenticated token, whatever its scopes. Runner lifecycle endpoints additionally enforce **run ownership**: only the runner token that claimed a run (or an admin) may report on it."},"462":{"id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes-22","page_id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes#bootstrap-token","content":"On first boot, if no access tokens exist, the Hub creates a `bootstrap-admin` token with the `admin`, `api`, `runner`, and `mcp` scopes and writes it to `data/bootstrap-token.txt` on the server (relative to the Hub's data directory). Use it to log in and mint narrower tokens, one per client or integration."},"463":{"id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes-23","page_id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes#browser-sessions","content":"The web app is an ordinary API client. `POST /api/auth/token-login` exchanges an access token for a **session cookie** — a signed copy of the token — so the browser session carries *exactly* the token's scopes, no extra power. Admin sections of the web app appear only for admin-scoped sessions. `POST /api/auth/logout` clears the cookie."},"464":{"id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes-24","page_id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes#telegram-webapp-sessions","content":"Approving from Telegram uses `POST /api/auth/telegram-webapp&#x60;, which verifies Telegram's signed init data against the configured bot and allowlisted users, then issues a session scoped to **`approvals` only** — narrower than any token session. A Telegram session can list and resolve approval cards but cannot start runs or touch admin surfaces."},"465":{"id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes-25","page_id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes#api--mcp","content":"Endpoint"},"466":{"id":"/concepts/tokens-and-scopes-2