"],[15,"3\\. Install the CLI and log in"],[727,"30 / minute"],[914,"32-byte key (base64/hex) for the encrypted secrets store. Keep it safe — rotating it makes stored secrets unreadable"],[16,"4\\. Start a runner"],[1102,"401 / 403 responses"],[17,"5\\. Run the hello workflow"],[18,"6\\. Watch the run and read the results"],[729,"60 / minute"],[731,"60 / minute"],[202,"A **post-run hook profile** is an admin-authored recipe for an optional side effect — publishing static output, pushing a work branch, calling a webhook — that runs *after* a run has produced its verified artifacts and its gates have passed. Hooks separate \"the work succeeded\" from \"the side effect happened\": callers opt in per run, and hook outcomes never rewrite a run's status."],[314,"A **run** is a single execution of a workflow with a JSON input. Runs are created from the API, MCP, web app, CLI, a schedule, or a workflow endpoint; a runner claims each queued run and executes it, streaming events, logs, and artifacts back to the Hub as the durable record."],[274,"A **runner** is a machine that executes runs. Runners run the Runyard runner process, which claims queued runs from the Hub and executes each workflow via the **Smithers engine** (`smithers up <workflow> --input <json>`), spawning the local agent CLI as the worker. Nothing is faked: the agent runs on the runner's machine, and the Hub is the durable record — events stream back as run events, and outputs and traces are uploaded as artifacts."],[373,"A **schedule** runs a workflow automatically: either recurring on a **cron** cadence or once at a fixed **runAt** timestamp. Each fire creates a completely ordinary run with the schedule's stored input — it appears in run lists, honors the workflow's approval policy, and is executed by whatever runner matches."],[523,"A **workflow package** is a portable `.runyard-workflow.json` file for moving a workflow between Hubs. Exports contain source bytes, metadata, requirements, and content/workflow hashes — never secret values. Imports publish the source as a new immutable bundle and create the workflow **disabled by default**, so an admin can configure and preflight it locally before enabling it. `validate` and `preview` let you check a package without writing anything."],[501,"A **workflow** is the unit of the Runyard catalog: a named, versioned definition of something an agent can do. Each workflow has a slug, a display name and description, input/output schemas, and a source program that the runner executes. In older code and database tables the same object is called a *capability* — that is the legacy/internal synonym; user-facing surfaces say workflow."],[112,"A card's `status` is only ever `pending` or `resolved`. What was decided and by what live in separate fields:"],[782,"A creator can make a card timed by supplying `timeoutMs` or `timeoutAt`, optionally with a `fallback` decision (`approve` or `reject`) — via `POST /api/approvals` or the `create_approval` MCP tool:"],[1031,"A deployed Hub checks the public GitHub Releases API passively (outbound-only, `UPDATE_CHECK_ENABLED`, default on) and shows admins an update badge."],[235,"A failed hook never rewrites a successful run into a failed one: the run keeps its own status and the hook results ride in the run output, aggregated into one headline hook status. `POST /api/hooks/{slug}/validate` is the admin dry-run: it reports `hook_config_required` with missing secret *names* only."],[721,"A few endpoints are rate-limited per client IP (over the limit returns `429`):"],[103,"A gated side effect asking permission before it runs."],[145,"A held run is cancelled, never failed."],[251,"A map of the core Runyard concepts and how they fit together."],[1163,"A minimal, real example"],[1116,"A quality gate (tests, lint, typecheck, build, eval) failed inside the workflow."],[1107,"A queued run means no runner has claimed it — either no runner is online, or none matches the run's required tags / requested location (`local` vs `vps`/`remote`)."],[1099,"A run is in `waiting_approval`"],[1098,"A run is stuck in `queued`"],[419,"A run receives the union of:"],[342,"A run request may include `responseEndpoint: {type: \"http\" | \"telegram\", config}` so the terminal-state reply is delivered to the caller when the run finishes. Delivery state is reported in `responseEndpoints[]` on `GET /api/runs/{id}`; polling that endpoint remains the canonical fallback."],[1108,"A runner is considered offline after \\~30 seconds without a heartbeat. If the runner should be online, check its service logs on the runner host:"],[876,"A running Hub also serves its own **client** install script at\n`https://hub.example.com/install.sh` (plus the CLI tarball at `/cli.tgz`). That\none installs the `runyard` CLI and `runyard-mcp` on a workstation — see\nthe CLI guide."],[2,"A self-hosted control plane for agent runs — workflows in, durable runs, logs, artifacts, and approvals out."],[166,"A specific artifact."],[448,"A token carries one or more scopes; each endpoint declares which scopes may call it."],[502,"A workflow definition carries:"],[56,"A workflow definition declares `requiredAgents` and `requiredSkills` as lists of catalog slugs; `describe_workflow` reports them alongside the schemas so a caller can see what a workflow depends on before running it. Workflow package exports record these requirements, and import preview reports whether the target Hub satisfies them."],[99,"A workflow paused at a gate; the decision releases or denies that step."],[281,"A workflow's `requiredRunnerTags` must all be present on the runner."],[709,"Abandon the negotiation"],[994,"Admin & updates"],[1146,"Admin actions (creating workflows, secrets, tokens, schedules) need `admin`; running workflows needs `api` or `mcp`; the runner protocol needs `runner`. Ask a Hub admin for a token with the right scopes."],[190,"Admin and setup views."],[249,"Admin readiness dry-run."],[839,"Admin-scoped commands:"],[542,"Admin; disables."],[569,"Admin; imports disabled."],[566,"Admin; nothing written."],[491,"Admin; who did what, most recent first."],[66,"Admin."],[69,"Admin."],[74,"Admin."],[77,"Admin."],[83,"Admin."],[86,"Admin."],[246,"Admin."],[399,"Admin."],[402,"Admin."],[405,"Admin."],[411,"Admin."],[438,"Admin."],[473,"Admin."],[479,"Admin."],[539,"Admin."],[557,"Admin."],[560,"Admin."],[563,"Admin."],[476,"Admin. `{name, scopes, expiresInDays?}`."],[435,"Admin. `{value, description?}`."],[396,"Admin. Body: `name`, `workflowSlug`, `cron` or `runAt`, `timezone`, `input`, `enabled`."],[533,"Admin. Inline source or `workflow.bundleId`."],[432,"Admin. Names and metadata only."],[1200,"Admins can export a workflow as a portable `.runyard-workflow.json` package file. It contains the workflow source bytes, metadata, requirements, and content hashes — never secret values."],[39,"Agent consumers — point AI agents at your Hub."],[40,"Agents, Skills & Knowledge"],[55,"All three are versioned and can be individually enabled/disabled."],[46,"Alongside workflows, the Hub maintains a shared catalog of reusable building blocks. They live in the database, are readable by any authenticated token, and are edited only by admins — so every workflow on the Hub draws from the same curated set."],[95,"An **approval** is a declared question with a declared consequence, presented to a human as a card in the web app, over Telegram, or through the API/MCP. Cards can hold a run before it executes (`waiting_approval`), pause a workflow mid-run at an engine gate, or simply record a decision. A run held on an approval waits indefinitely — waiting never fails it."],[744,"An approval is a declared question with a declared consequence. Cards carry an *ask* — who is asked, what approving does, and why a human is needed — and every surface renders that stored ask verbatim. A run held on a card sits in `waiting_approval` and is never failed or age-reaped for waiting."],[111,"An ask without both `action` and `reason` is tr