delivering"],[743,"Telegram WebApp login"],[444,"Telegram WebApp sessions"],[330,"Terminal failure; see failure classes below."],[1111,"Terminal failures carry a class so you know whether to fix input, config, or infrastructure:"],[331,"Terminal states are final: late reports racing a terminal state are absorbed idempotently rather than overwriting the first decision."],[748,"The **Approvals** view lists pending cards with their ask, consequences, and buttons."],[956,"The `--remote <name>` argument, resolved against the saved remotes in\n`~/.runyard/config.json` (written by `runyard login`)"],[720,"The `422`/`409` bodies are returned by `run` with `negotiate: true` and by\ndraft `submit`; they are structured responses, not opaque failures — answer the\nquestions and retry."],[816,"The `runyard` CLI is a thin client of the Hub's HTTP API. It talks\nto one or more Hubs (\"remotes\"), starts and tails workflow runs, resolves\napprovals, and can set up and start a runner on the local machine."],[365,"The `start`/`complete`/`fail`/event-append and artifact-upload endpoints under `/api/runs/{id}` are the runner protocol (runner-scoped tokens, run ownership enforced) — see Runners."],[1128,"The agent's output failed schema validation."],[127,"The API exposes these as `whatHappensIfApproved` / `whatHappensIfRejected` / `whatHappensIfChangesRequested` / `whatHappensIfIgnored` in each card's `context`, alongside the ask, the linked run, and deep links."],[192,"The API hands these links back so agents and integrations can point humans at the right screen without building URLs themselves:"],[574,"The API-first guarantee"],[90,"The ask contract"],[881,"The bootstrap script installs these for you, retargeted to your install\ndirectory, env-file location, and node binary. Secrets live in the\n`EnvironmentFile`s (mode `0600`), never in the units."],[791,"The bot's API token."],[219,"The caller selects profiles per run with `input.postRunHooks: [\"publish-docs\", …]`."],[282,"The caller's execution intent: `executionMode: \"local\" | \"remote\" | \"auto\"` (optionally a specific `runnerLocation`). `remote` targets the shared remote/VPS pool (default location `vps`); `auto` takes any matching runner."],[252,"The catalog"],[493,"The catalog unit of Runyard - versioned definitions with schemas, immutable source bundles, and portable packages."],[819,"The CLI stores named remotes (Hub URL + token) in `~/.runyard/config.json`\n(mode `0600`). Every command accepts global options `--url`, `--token`,\n`--remote <name>`, and `--json` (machine-readable output)."],[591,"The complete MCP tool set (parity-tested against the API surface). Connect with `runyard mcp install` or the `runyard-mcp` stdio server."],[1199,"The corresponding MCP tools are `get_workflow_source`, `list_workflow_bundles`, and `get_workflow_bundle` (which does include the source). You can also publish a bundle directly with `POST /api/workflow-bundles` / `publish_workflow_bundle` and reference it by `workflow.bundleId`, but prefer inline source — the Hub publishes the bundle for you."],[106,"The creator of a card states the ask up front, and every surface renders it verbatim:"],[957,"The current saved remote"],[769,"The decision is applied to the paused workflow on the runner and it resumes past the gate."],[413,"The encrypted secret store - admin-managed, listable by name only, delivered to runs at claim time and never returned by the API."],[817,"The fastest path is the install script served by your own Hub, which downloads\nthe CLI tarball from the same instance (`/cli.tgz`), installs `runyard` and\n`runyard-mcp` into `~/.local/bin`, and logs you in:"],[588,"The full HTTP surface, generated from the Hub's API surface registry — it cannot drift from the routes the server actually registers."],[777,"The gated side effect is allowed to run."],[1013,"The GitHub Actions pipeline (`.github/workflows/release.yml` and `images.yml`) has four jobs:"],[765,"The held run is released to the queue and executes."],[234,"The hook did not run."],[786,"The Hub can post approval cards to a Telegram chat and accept decisions from the buttons on them."],[896,"The Hub is a single HTTP listener; any TLS-terminating proxy that forwards **all\npaths** to the Hub port works. With Caddy:"],[877,"The Hub listens on `127.0.0.1:43117` by default. Start a runner in a second\nprocess:"],[867,"The Hub uses the built-in `node:sqlite` module (started with `--experimental-sqlite`)"],[594,"The live, private catalog: workflows with schemas, execution modes, runner pool state, and ready-to-use CLI/MCP invocations."],[268,"The machines that claim and execute runs via the Smithers engine - registration, tags, capacity, health, and sandboxing."],[947,"The parity guarantee"],[889,"The portable base stack is `docker-compose.yml` at the repo root:"],[376,"The preview returns a human-readable description plus the next fire instants — nothing is created."],[230,"The profile cannot execute — typically missing named secrets or a disabled secret store."],[232,"The profile was not eligible for this run."],[1009,"The release-train helper"],[873,"The repository ships a one-command, idempotent bootstrap script for a fresh\nLinux box:"],[879,"The repository ships generic units in `deploy/`. The Hub unit\n(`deploy/runyard.service`):"],[21,"The repository's install script is a one-command, idempotent bootstrap. It installs Node 22 and pnpm if needed, clones Runyard at the latest release tag (default `/opt/runyard`), generates an env file with a `SECRETS_ENC_KEY` and session secret, creates the data directory, and installs systemd units for the Hub and a runner:"],[1085,"The reusable secret store is enabled by setting `SECRETS_ENC_KEY` (a 32-byte key) on the Hub; without a valid key the feature is disabled rather than degraded. Values are encrypted at rest and are write-only from the API's point of view: `GET /api/secrets` returns names and metadata, never values, and secrets are redacted from API responses, events, approval cards, and audit entries. Workflows reference secrets by name; the Hub injects values into runs that declared them."],[1125,"The run exceeded a deadline or an operation timed out."],[421,"the run input's `input.secretNames` list."],[767,"The run is cancelled — a human \"no\" is a decision, not a failure."],[766,"The run is cancelled; your note tells the requester what to change."],[1110,"The run is held on an approval card, which is by design: approval-held runs are never failed or reaped for waiting. Find and resolve the card — web **Approvals**, `runyard approvals` then `runyard approve|reject|request-changes <approval-id>`, or the MCP tools. See Approvals."],[306,"The run lifecycle, preflight and run drafts, events and artifacts, reruns, and promotion."],[878,"The runner authenticates with a runner-scoped token (`RUNYARD_HUB_TOKEN`); on a\nfresh Hub it may use the bootstrap token until you mint one."],[304,"The runner protocol endpoints intentionally have no MCP tools — they are Hub↔runner machinery, not an operator surface."],[625,"The runner protocol: register, heartbeat, claim runs, report lifecycle events and artifacts"],[456,"The runner protocol: register, heartbeat, claim runs, report lifecycle, upload artifacts."],[1079,"The runner protocol: register, heartbeat, claim runs, report lifecycle."],[1119,"The runner's preflight refused to execute (missing workflow source, auth not ready, repo path problems)."],[36,"The same data lives at `GET /api/runs/{id}`, `/api/runs/{id}/timeline`, `/api/runs/{id}/logs`, and `/api/runs/{id}/artifacts`, and in the web run page — the Hub is the source of truth even when execution happened on a local runner."],[454,"The same operating surface for MCP clients."],[1077,"The same operations over the MCP server."],[623,"The same operations, issued for MCP clients"],[23,"The script never prints secrets, never applies updates automatically, and prints a Caddy reverse-proxy snippet if you want TLS in front (recommended for anything non-local — see the security guide)."],[959,"The server exposes **85 tools**, generated from the same API surface registry\nthe Hub's routes and `/openapi.json` come from. Grouped by resource:"],[954,"The server name is `runyard` for the default remote and `runyard-<remote>` for\nothers, so one client can talk to several Hubs. &#x2A;*No token is stored in client\nconfigs.** At startup the server resolves its target in this order:"],[41,"The shared catalog of reusable agent roles, skills, and knowledge resources that workflows reference."],[186,"The shared catalogs (append `/:slug` for one entry)."],[226,"The side effect completed."],[779,"The side effect is skipped; the run's completed work is unaffected."],[778,"The side effect is skipped; your note explains what to change."],[228,"The side effect itself failed."],[1194,"The source is a small Smithers TSX workflow (modeled on the seeded `hello` workflow): one task, structured output validated with Zod."],[42,"The three catalogs"],[958,"The token's scopes decide what the tools may do — a token with `mcp` scope can\ndiscover, preflight, and run workflows; `admin` unlocks the admin tools listed\nbelow."],[1000,"The tool list, the HTTP routes, and `/openapi.json` are all generated from one\nregistry, and a test fails the build when they drift: **every Hub API operation\nis either exposed as an MCP tool or carries a documented exemption** (exempt\noperations are browser pages, install assets, the runner-to-Hub machine\nprotocol, SSE streams that tools cover by polling, and legacy aliases). If you\ncan do it in the web UI or over HTTP, your agent can do it over MCP."],[946,"The tool surface"],[608,"The typical flow"],[463,"The web app is an ordinary API client. `POST /api/auth/token-login` exchanges an access token for a **session cookie** — a signed copy of the token — so the browser session carries *exactly* the token's scopes, no extra power. Admin sections of the web app appear only for admin-scoped sessions. `POST /api/auth/logout` clears the cookie."],[596,"The web app is an ordinary client of the same HTTP API, with no privileged endpoints. Every route is declared in one registry that also generates `openapi.json` and is parity-tested against the MCP tool list — so a lossless third-party client is possible by construction: anything the web app can show or do, your client can too, over HTTP or MCP."],[1202,"The web app's workflow create/edit screens are ordinary clients of `POST /api/workflows` and `PATCH /api/workflows/{id}`: they submit the definition with inline source bytes and the Hub publishes the bundle, exactly as above. There is no separate, privileged authoring path."],[1166,"The web editor"],[1134,"The workflow concluded a human must act."],[218,"The workflow must opt in via `workflow.hooks.allowedProfiles` (a list of profile slugs, or `\"*\"`); no opt-in means no hooks, default-closed."],[1191,"The workflow source bytes, sent inline as a string (aliases: `workflow.sourceBytes`, `workflow.code`)."],[420,"the workflow's declared `workflow.secrets` list, and"],[176,"The workflow's runs."],[951,"Then let the CLI write your AI client's MCP config:"],[897,"Then set `BASE_URL=https://hub.example.com` in the Hub's env file and restart.\nAn `https://` base URL switches the Hub into production session mode. If the\nproxy is not on loopback, set the trust-proxy configuration accordingly so\nclient IPs (used by rate limiting) are read from `X-Forwarded-For` only when\nthat header is trustworthy."],[842,"Then start the runner against the current remote (it inherits the remote's URL\nand token, or `RUNYARD_HUB_URL` / `RUNYARD_HUB_TOKEN`):"],[20,"This page takes you from a fresh Linux box to a completed workflow run with logs and artifacts in the Hub."],[334,"Three ways to use it:"],[738,"Timed approvals and fallback"],[92,"Timed approvals with fallback"],[953,"To configure a client by hand, print the snippet instead:"],[30,"To run an ad-hoc runner on any other machine (for example your laptop, for `local` execution):"],[590,"token"],[593,"token"],[470,"Token name and scopes."],[980,"Tokens"],[439,"Tokens & Scopes"],[617,"Tokens are minted by an admin (web UI, `POST /api/tokens`, or the CLI) and carry\n**scopes**:"],[1071,"Tokens carry scopes; admins mint them from the Connect tab or `POST /api/tokens`."],[812,"Tokens, audit, and catalog"],[961,"Tools"],[998,"Tools marked † require an admin-scoped token."],[1015,"Trigger"],[213,"Trigger a preview deploy for a configured project."],[1096,"Troubleshooting"],[1046,"Trust boundary"],[1045,"Trust boundary, token scopes, secrets handling, runner sandboxing, and production posture for a Runyard deployment."],[841,"Turn a machine into a runner in three steps. First scaffold a workspace\n(requires `bun` and the `smithers` engine on `PATH`; it warns if no `claude`,\n`codex`, or `pi` agent CLI is found):"],[1070,"Two narrow exceptions authenticate by other means: `POST /api/telegram/webhook` is verified against the configured bot and webhook secret, and `POST /api/workflow-endpoints/{slug}` submissions authenticate with that endpoint's own secret (below). `GET /api/setup` returns only a reduced identity payload (instance name, auth mode) to unauthenticated callers."],[1137,"Unclassified failure."],[658,"Unified ascending timeline (`since=<iso>`, `limit=<n>`); backs `runyard tail`"],[1155,"Unified timeline: status transitions, events, artifacts as NDJSON."],[815,"Updating a host install"],[1164,"Updating a workflow"],[522,"Updating a workflow bumps its integer `version` and snapshots the previous definition. `GET /api/workflows/{name}/versions` lists the versions observed on past runs, and every run records the `workflowVersion` it executed. Bundle versions count separately, per publish."],[114,"Values"],[788,"Variable"],[899,"Variable"],[920,"Variable"],[22,"Verify the Hub is up:"],[1148,"Verify, in order: `TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN` and `TELEGRAM_APPROVAL_CHAT_ID` are set on the Hub; the bot's webhook points at `https://hub.example.com/api/telegram/webhook` with the matching `TELEGRAM_WEBHOOK_SECRET`; the bot is a member of the target chat; and the users pressing buttons are listed in `TELEGRAM_APPROVAL_USER_IDS`. Response-endpoint deliveries record their state (`status`, `attempts`, `last_error`) on `GET /api/runs/{id}` under `responseEndpoints[]`."],[497,"Versioning"],[1006,"Versioning and releases"],[548,"Versions seen on runs."],[156,"View"],[172,"Visual graph tab."],[1123,"Wait and re-run; check the provider account."],[809,"Watch and manage runs"],[747,"Web app"],[33,"Web: open **Workflows**, pick &#x2A;*Hello (Smithers proof)**, fill in `topic`, and click Run."],[741,"Webhook"],[371,"What a fire produces"],[759,"What each decision does depends on the card's kind:"],[1,"What is Runyard"],[1016,"What it does"],[582,"What it gives you"],[48,"What it is"],[97,"What it represents"],[1151,"What it tells you"],[1053,"What stays out of public discovery docs"],[1177,"What the workflow does; shown in the catalog and menus."],[1114,"What to do"],[195,"When an agent hands off to a human — \"approve this\", \"read the logs\" — prefer relaying the payload's deep link over describing where to click."],[875,"When it finishes it prints next steps: sign in with the bootstrap token, mint a\nrunner-scoped token, put it in `/etc/runyard/runner.env`, and restart the runner\nunit."],[736,"Where approvals appear"],[858,"Where state lives"],[19,"Where to go next"],[1106,"Where to look, generally"],[514,"Whether new runs hold for an approval before executing."],[1187,"Whether runs hold for a human approval before executing (`{ \"required\": true }`)."],[44,"Who can edit"],[1157,"Who did what (admin)."],[637,"With `\"negotiate\": true`, a non-ready request returns the negotiation state\n(questions, blockers, warnings, plus a saved draft) instead of creating a run —\nfix the input and call again."],[120,"With a `fallback` decision (`approve` or `reject`), the configured decision is applied automatically when the timer elapses, recorded with `resolvedVia: \"fallback_timer\"`."],[631,"with status `403`. `GET /api/me` describes the calling token (name and scopes)."],[121,"Without a fallback, the elapsed card is flagged `fallback_required` and keeps waiting — no decision is invented, and the linked run is never failed by an elapsed timer."],[988,"Workflow bundles"],[168,"Workflow catalog."],[170,"Workflow detail."],[986,"Workflow endpoints"],[1049,"Workflow endpoints"],[498,"Workflow packages"],[811,"Workflow packages"],[990,"Workflow packages"],[999,"Workflow source is always created and edited **through these tools** —\n`create_workflow` / `update_workflow` take inline source bytes or an existing\n`workflow.bundleId`, and `import_workflow_package` installs a portable package\nas a disabled workflow. Bare file paths on the runner are rejected."],[519,"Workflow source is created and edited through the API/MCP (`create_workflow` / `update_workflow` with inline source bytes) or by importing a workflow package. You never write workflow files to disk on the Hub or runner: custom workflows must carry source bytes or reference an existing `workflow.bundleId` — bare `workflow.entry` file paths are rejected."],[495,"Workflow source is data, not files"],[646,"Workflow source, parsed metadata, sections, graph"],[492,"Workflows"],[964,"Workflows"],[638,"Workflows and runs (`preflight` and `run` require `api` or `mcp` scope; reads\nrequire any token):"],[1167,"Workflows are stored in the Hub database as immutable, versioned source bundles. You create or update a workflow by sending its definition — **including the workflow source bytes** — over HTTP (`POST /api/workflows`, `PATCH /api/workflows/{id}`) or MCP (`create_workflow` / `update_workflow`). The Hub publishes the source as a hash-addressed bundle and records its id on the definition as `workflow.bundleId`."],[682,"Workflows can pause on a human decision. Approval cards are first-class API\nobjects (resolving them requires `api`, `mcp`, or `approvals` scope):"],[838,"Workflows move between Hubs as portable `.runyard-workflow.json` package files\n— exported from one Hub and imported into another (admin token required).\nImported workflows arrive **disabled** for review before enabling; this is the\nsupported way to carry workflow source around, not files on a runner."],[1087,"Workflows whose consequences warrant a human get an `approvalPolicy` that holds runs in `waiting_approval` until someone approves; mid-run engine gates and gated side effects (post-run hook profiles are admin-defined and admin-configured) use the same approval cards. See Approvals."],[927,"Workspace directory the runner executes workflows in"]],"type":"string"},"page_id":{"docs":{"1":0,"2":1,"3":2,"4":3,"5":4,"6":5,"7":6,"8":7,"9":8,"10":9,"11":1173,"12":1174,"13":1175,"14":1176,"15":1177,"16":1178,"17":1179,"18":1180,"19":1181,"20":1182,"21":1183,"22":1184,"23":1185,"24":1186,"25":1187,"26":1188,"27":1189,"28":1190,"29":1191,"30":1192,"31":1193,"32":1194,"33":1195,"34":1196,"35":1197,"36":1198,"37":1199,"38":1200,"39":1201,"40":27,"41":28,"42":29,"43":30,"44":31,"45":32,"46":33,"47":34,"48":35,"49":36,"50":37,"51":38,"52":39,"53":40,"54":41,"55":42,"56":43,"57":44,"58":45,"59":46,"60":47,"61":48,"62":49,"63":50,"64":51,"65":52,"66":53,"67":54,"68":55,"69":56,"70":57,"71":58,"72":59,"73":60,"74":61,"75":62,"76":63,"77":64,"78":65,"79":66,"80":67,"81":68,"82":69,"83":70,"84":71,"85":72,"86":73,"87":74,"88":75,"89":76,"90":77,"91":78,"92":79,"93":80,"94":81,"95":82,"96":83,"97":84,"98":85,"99":86,"100":87,"101":88,"102":89,"103":90,"104":91,"105":92,"106":93,"107":94,"108":95,"109":96,"110":97,"111":98,"112":99,"113":100,"114":101,"115":102,"116":103,"117":104,"118":105,"119":106,"120":107,"121":108,"122":109,"123":110,"124":111,"125":112,"126":113,"127":114,"128":115,"129":116,"130":117,"131":118,"132":119,"133":120,"134":121,"135":122,"136":123,"137":124,"138":125,"139":126